				<li id="16578599" class="cmnt-root" data="37" data-d="1648564340000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t579962/Gelmir-Glintstone-Staff" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">29 Mar 2022 10:32</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16578599" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">Testing with a max-upgrade Gelmir Staff, putting 5 points at a time into Int or Faith and recording the Sorcery Scaling each time, here&apos;s the caps I found:<br/><br/>Each point of Int/Faith adds 3.6 Sorc Scaling until Int/Faith is at 30<br/>Each point of Int/Faith adds 1.6 Sorc Scaling between 30 and 45<br/>Each point of Int/Faith adds 0.55 Sorc Scaling after 45<br/><br/>so the soft cap for this staff is 30 and the hard cap is 45.  Both Int and Faith have these caps, and both contribute equally to scaling.<br/><br/>Note that the Rykard&apos;s Rancor spell needs 40 int, so if you want the best bang for your stats using that spell and this staff, you&apos;d probably want to go 40 int and 30 faith</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16578599" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16578599" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">4</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span><